{"key":"post-11854944","value":"<?xml version=\"1.0\"?>\n<post>\n<id>11854944</id>\n<content>&lt;/font&gt;&lt;blockquote&gt;&lt;font class=&quot;small&quot;&gt;Quote:&lt;/font&gt;&lt;hr /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;b&gt;&lt;i&gt;screekrunner said:&lt;/i&gt;&lt;/b&gt;&lt;br /&gt;Do you guys boil it for an hour? &lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;hr /&gt;&lt;/blockquote&gt;&lt;font class=&quot;post&quot;&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;No, much longer.&amp;nbsp; Your jars should be elevated &lt;i&gt;above&lt;/i&gt; the water, not in it.&amp;nbsp; It isn't about when the water boils, but when the steam begins to surround the jars after the thermal inertia of the cold jars has been overcome.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;Use a pot with a tight fitting lid, and don't begin counting the time until steam is escaping from under the lid.&amp;nbsp; At this point, turn down the stove to the minimum setting that will keep steam escaping, but just barely.&amp;nbsp; Time for &lt;b&gt;90 minutes&lt;/b&gt; after that point.&amp;nbsp; Add water if necessary during the cycle to keep the pot from boiling dry.&amp;nbsp; It's OK to open the lid to look in and see how much water is left.&amp;nbsp; If you see you're going to need more water, it's a good idea to boil it in another small pan first and then pour it in, thus you don't cool off your sterilization pot.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;You can see a video of the whole process on my &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.mushroomvideos.com/BRF-Pf-Tek&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot; rel=&quot;nofollow noreferrer noopener&quot;&gt;website&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;br /&gt;RR</content>\n<name>RogerRabbit</name>\n<next>11855182</next>\n<prev>11854920</prev>\n<first>11854450</first>\n<last>11855610</last>\n<when>1263863325</when>\n<utime>01/19/10 03:08 AM</utime>\n</post>"}